{
  "texts": [
    "word2vec [30]), which represent a word as the same vector regardless of its context, and directional models (e.g.",
    "LSTM [35]), which only capture sequential dependencies (left-to-right and/or right-to-left).",
    "For example, word2vec will have the same embedding for the bark of a tree and the bark of a dog, while a Transformer will look at the surrounding words to generate an embedding that captures the meaning of bark based on the context in which it occurs.",
    "Unlike word2vec, which learns a single embedding per word, BERT breaks down words into subwords, allowing it to model embeddings for individual characters all the way through to complete words [9].",
    "By combining subword embeddings, a BERT model can generate vector representations of out-of-vocabulary words, increasing its utility across different corpora and domains."
  ]
}